value.value: A biological tissue mass, most commonly a mass of nerve cell bodies.
Multicellular, connected anatomical structure that has multiple organs as parts and whose parts work together to achieve some shared function.

definition.value: Connected anatomical system that forms a barrier between an animal and its environment. In vertebrates, the integumental system consists of the epidermis, dermis plus associated glands and adnexa such as hair and scales. In invertebrates, the integumental system may include cuticle.

value.value: The procuticle that is not tanned (sclerotised, proteins scarcely crosslinked) and located between the Schmidt's layer and the exocuticle.
The cuticle that does not contain chitin fibrils and is located externally of the exocuticle.

The nervous system is an organ system containing predominantly neuron and glial cells. In bilaterally symmetrical organism, it is arranged in a network of tree-like structures connected to a central body.
The nerve that innervates the antenna.
The nerve that innervates the labium
The nerve that innervates the mandible.
The nerve that innervates the maxilla.
A system of neurons that has the specialized function to produce and secrete hormones, and that constitutes, in whole or in part, an endocrine organ or system.
One of a pair of separate or fused bodies in many insects that are sometimes closely associated with the corpora cardiaca and that secrete hormones (as juvenile hormone)

One of a pair of neurohemal organs located on the walls of the aorta just behind the brain. The corpora cardiaca release their store of PTTH only after they receive a signal from neurosecretory cells in the brain.
